',{id:"hsus_homeownership_rate_1890_2024",title:"US homeownership rate 1890-2024 - the long view on the American Dream",sub:"1900: 47% homeownership. 1940: 44%. 1960: 62% (peak post-WWII suburban expansion). 2004: 69% (bubble peak). 2024: 65.6%. The homeownership rate has barely moved since 1960 despite 60 years of housing policy. The suburban dream was built in a single decade.",type:"CHART",geo:"us_national",fmt:"Line chart",tbl:"HSUS Dc series homeownership 1890-2000 + Census CPS 2001-2024",section:"Housing",ext:["FRED: any national economic time series (fred.stlouisfed.org - free API)","HUD Fair Market Rents + housing data by state/county (huduser.gov - free)"],vars:["home_price_index_2024","housing_permits_total"],join:["median_household_income","mortgage_delinquency_rate","pct_bachelors"],sc:{emotional:6,relatability:7,surprise:7,tension:4,visual:7,data_ready:9,originality:6},vs:64,tags:"homeownership rate 1890 2024 1900 47% 1940 44% 1960 62% 2004 69% 2024 65.6% barely moved 60 years policy suburban decade WWII HSUS Dc Census CPS"}',
',{id:"hsus_energy_consumption_by_source_1850_2024",title:"US energy consumption by source 1850-2024 - the three energy transitions",sub:"1850: 90% wood. 1910: coal dominates at 77%. 1970: oil and gas at 73%. 2024: fossil fuels still 79%, but solar and wind now 4.8% and growing at 15% per year. The first two energy transitions took 60 years each. The third has 40 years of runway if it maintains pace.",type:"CHART",geo:"us_national",fmt:"Area chart",tbl:"HSUS Db energy series 1850-2000 + EIA 2001-2024",section:"Energy",ext:["FRED: any national economic time series (fred.stlouisfed.org - free API)","EIA State Energy Data System: production + consumption by state (eia.gov - free API)"],vars:["renewable_energy_share","coal_consumption"],join:["energy_consumption_per_capita","oil_gas_extraction_index","hydroelectric_consumption"],sc:{emotional:7,relatability:6,surprise:8,tension:6,visual:9,data_ready:9,originality:7},vs:72,tags:"energy consumption source 1850 2024 wood 90% coal 77% oil gas 73% fossil 79% solar wind 4.8% 15% per year three transitions 60 years HSUS Db EIA"}',
